questions.question: A 29-year-old woman presents with lower abdominal pain and vaginal spotting at 7 weeks of gestation. An ultrasound confirms an ectopic pregnancy. Which of the following statements about progesterone in ectopic pregnancy is most accurate? pregnancies.

options.A: Progesterone levels are typically higher in ectopic pregnancies compared to normal intrauterine
options.B: Low serum progesterone levels can help differentiate between ectopic and intrauterine pregnancies.
options.C: Progesterone is used as a first-line treatment for ectopic pregnancies.
options.D: High progesterone levels are a definitive indicator of a viable intrauterine pregnancy

questions.explanation: intrauterine pregnancies. intrauterine pregnancies . Explanation: Low serum progesterone levels can help differentiate between ectopic and intrauterine pregnancies, as lower levels are often associated with non-viable pregnancies, including ectopic pregnancies. Serum progesterone levels: >25 ng/ml indicates viable intrauterine pregnancy < 5 ng/ml indicates non-viable intrauterine pregnancy or ectopic pregnancy (Option A) Higher progesterone levels are generally indicative of a normal, viable intrauterine pregnancy (Option C) Progesterone is not used as a treatment for ectopic pregnancies. (Option D) High progesterone levels are not used as a definitive marker. Reference: Williams Obstetrics, 26th Edition, Page 176, 177, 665, 733

questions.question: Which is the most common non-tubal site for an ectopic pregnancy?
questions.explanation: most common non-tubal site is the ovary In the tubes: Ampulla > Isthmus > Infundibulum > Interstitial (least common) Abdominal ectopic pregnancy is one of the least common sites of ectopic pregnancy (Option C) Tubal ectopic pregnancy ends at: Isthmus: 6 weeks Ampulla: 8 weeks Interstitium 10-12 weeks (since interstitium is close to the uterus, myometrium supports the pregnancy, hence it is the longest tubal ectopic pregnancy. It is the most dangerous type of ectopic pregnancy as well.) Site for the longest duration of ectopic pregnancy: Abdominal ectopic Reference: Williams Obstetrics, 26th Edition, Page 200, 201

questions.question: A 34-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with acute lower abdominal pain and vaginal bleeding. She has a positive pregnancy test. Her medical history includes a previous chlamydial infection and smoking. She also developed GDM and was preeclamptic in her last pregnancy. Which of the following is the most likely risk factor contributing to her ectopic pregnancy?
questions.explanation: significant risk factor for ectopic pregnancy. Pelvic inflammatory disease (PID), often caused by sexually transmitted infections like chlamydia, can lead to scarring and damage of the fallopian tubes, increasing the risk of an ectopic pregnancy. Risk Factors of Ectopic Pregnancy History of PID History of infertility History of tubal ligation ART particularly if the tubes are patent but damaged Contraception failure Intrauterine Contraceptive Device (IUCD) use Previous ectopic pregnancy Previous induced abortion Tubal reconstructive surgery Tubal endometriosis Reference: Williams Obstetrics, 26th Edition, Page221, 222, 223

questions.question: A 30-year-old woman presents with lower abdominal pain and vaginal spotting at 6 weeks of gestation. An ultrasound reveals an ectopic pregnancy. Which of the following symptoms is more indicative of a ruptured ectopic pregnancy compared to an unruptured ectopic pregnancy?
questions.explanation: Correct answer: B) Abdominal distension and severe pain Explanation: Abdominal distension and severe pain are more indicative of a ruptured ectopic pregnancy, which can cause significant intra-abdominal bleeding and require urgent medical intervention. Clinical presentation of Ectopic pregnancy (Triad) Abdominal pain (Most consistent feature) Amenorrhoea Vaginal bleeding Mild pelvic discomfort (Option A) and Asymptomatic presentations (Option D) are more common in unruptured ectopic pregnancies. Regular menstrual cycles (Option C) are not related to the symptoms of an ectopic pregnancy. Reference: Williams Obstetrics, 26th Edition, Page221-232

questions.question: A 28-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with a sudden onset of severe lower abdominal pain, dizziness, and shoulder tip pain. She has a history of amenorrhea for the past 7 weeks and a positive pregnancy test. On physical examination, she is pale, with a blood pressure of 90/60 mmHg and a heart rate of 120 beats per minute. Which of the following diagnostic findings is most indicative of a ruptured ectopic pregnancy?

options.B: The presence of a gestational sac in the uterine cavity on ultrasound
options.C: Free fluid in the abdomen on ultrasound
options.D: Absence of adnexal mass on pelvic exam

questions.explanation: on ultrasound is a key diagnostic finding indicative of a ruptured ectopic pregnancy, often representing blood from the rupture. Investigations for ectopic pregnancy: Blood examination should be done as a routine for: Haemoglobin ABO and Rh grouping Total white cell count and differential count Erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR) Estimation of β -hCG: The suspicious findings are: Lower concentration of β -hCG compared to normal intrauterine pregnancy Plasma concentration does not double in 48 hours like in normal pregnancy Sonography (TVS): The diagnostic features are: Absence of intrauterine pregnancy with a positive pregnancy test. Fluid (echogenic) in the pouch of Douglas. Adnexal mass clearly separated from the ovary (Blob sign). Rarely cardiac motion may be seen in an unruptured tubal ectopic pregnancy. Combination of quantitative β -hCG values and sonography: TVS provides visualization of a well-formed intrauterine gestational sac as early as 4–5 weeks from the last menstrual period. The lowest level of serum β -hCG at which a gestational sac is consistently visible using TVS (discriminatory zone) is ≥ 1,500 IU/L.So if the beta-hCG level is ≥ 1,500 and no intrauterine pregnancy is seen, an ectopic pregnancy is highly suspected. Laparoscopy offers benefits in cases of confusion with other pelvic lesions. Dilatation and curettage: Identification of decidua without villi structure is suggestive. Serum progesterone: A level greater than 25 ng/mL is suggestive of viable intrauterine pregnancy whereas a level less than 5 ng/mL suggests an ectopic or abnormal intrauterine pregnancy. Laparotomy offers benefits when in doubt. Elevated serum hCG (Option A) levels and the presence of a gestational sac (Option B) in the uterine cavity are not specific to a ruptured ectopic pregnancy. Absence of adnexal mass on the pelvic exam (Option D): The absence of an adnexal mass on the pelvic exam does not rule out an ectopic pregnancy, especially if a rupture has occurred. Reference: Williams Obstetrics, 26th Edition, Page220, 222, 223

questions.question: A 28-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with severe lower abdominal pain and dizziness with a history of amenorrhea for the past 8 weeks. On examination, she is pale, diaphoretic, and hypotensive with a blood pressure of 80/50 mmHg and a heart rate of 120 bpm. An ultrasound confirms a ruptured ectopic pregnancy with significant intra-abdominal bleeding. The patient is in shock and requires immediate surgical intervention. Which of the following surgical procedures is most appropriate for this patient?
questions.explanation: Correct Answer: D) Laparotomy with total salpingectomy Explanation: Laparotomy with Total Salpingectomy is the definitive management for ruptured ectopic pregnancy with shock as it allows for rapid access to the abdominal cavity, control of haemorrhage, and complete removal of the ectopic pregnancy, which is crucial in a hemodynamically unstable patient. Total salpingectomy is done and not partial salpingectomy as it can potentially lead to another ectopic in the future. (Option A and C) The Laparoscopic approach is suitable only for hemodynamically stable patients. (Option B) Reference: Williams Obstetrics, 26th Edition, Page222, 223

questions.question: A 32-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with acute lower abdominal pain and vaginal bleeding. She has a history of amenorrhea for the past 7 weeks and reports dizziness and lightheadedness. Her vitals indicate hypotension with a blood pressure of 90/60 mmHg and a heart rate of 110 bpm. Transvaginal ultrasound is unavailable at the facility. The physician decides to perform a culdocentesis to aid in the diagnosis. Which of the following findings from the culdocentesis would suggest a ruptured ectopic pregnancy?

options.A: Clear fluid aspirated from the pouch of Douglas
options.B: Clotting blood with a hematocrit greater than 15%
options.C: Non-clotting blood with a hematocrit greater than 15%
options.D: Purulent fluid aspirated from the pouch of Douglas

questions.explanation: Correct Answer: C) Non-clotting blood with a hematocrit greater than 15% Explanation: Culdocentesis is a diagnostic procedure that involves the aspiration of fluid from the pouch of Douglas (the rectouterine pouch) through the posterior fornix of the vagina using an 18-gauge lumbar puncture needle fitted with a syringe. This procedure is useful for diagnosing ruptured ectopic when diagnostic tools such as transvaginal ultrasound (TVS) or laparoscopy are not available. Non-clotting blood with a hematocrit greater than 15% in the aspirate suggests a ruptured ectopic pregnancy.

questions.question: A 27-year-old woman presents to the clinic with lower abdominal pain and vaginal spotting. She has a history of amenorrhea for 7 weeks. On examination, she is hemodynamically stable. The physician suspects an unruptured ectopic pregnancy and advises USG evaluation with beta hCG assay. Which of the following findings is not typically seen for diagnosing an unruptured ectopic pregnancy? ≥ 1,500 IU/L. β -hCG by 48 hours along with an empty uterus

options.A: Absence of intrauterine pregnancy on Transabdominal sonography with beta hCG levels
options.B: Failure to double the value of
options.C: Adnexal mass clearly separated from the ovary
options.D: Presence of ring-of-fire pattern on Colour Doppler TVS

questions.explanation: hCG levels ≥ 1,500 IU/L. Correct Answer: A) Absence of intrauterine pregnancy on Transabdominal sonography with beta hCG levels ≥ 1,500 IU/L Explanation: Transabdominal sonography (TAS) is less sensitive than transvaginal sonography (TVS) for early pregnancy detection. The discriminatory zone for TAS is typically β -hCG ≥ 6,000 IU/L. Therefore, the absence of an intrauterine pregnancy on TAS at a β -hCG level of ≥ 1,500 IU/L is not typically used for diagnosing ectopic pregnancy as it is not a reliable threshold for TAS . TVS should be used for a more accurate diagnosis at a β -hCG level of ≥ 1,500 IU/L. Findings for Diagnosing Unruptured Ectopic Pregnancy Diagnostic Modality Findings for Unruptured Ectopic Pregnancy Transvaginal Sonography (TVS) Absence of Intrauterine Pregnancy: No gestational sac within the uterine cavity when β -hCG ≥ 1500 IU/L. Adnexal Mass: An adnexal mass clearly separate from the ovary (Blob sign). (Option C) Ring-of-Fire Pattern: Increased blood flow around the ectopic mass on Color Doppler. (Option D) Presence of pseudo gestational sac. Free fluid in the Pouch of Douglas Transabdominal Sonography (TAS) Absence of Intrauterine Pregnancy: No gestational sac when β -hCG ≥ 6,000 IU/L Other features: May be visible but less sensitive than TVS for smaller masses Beta hCG Levels Failure to double the value of β -hCG in 48 hours (Option B) Lower concentration of β -hCG than expected for gestational age Reference: Williams Obstetrics, 26th Edition, Page222-226

questions.question: A 30-year-old woman presents to the clinic with lower abdominal pain and bleeding. She has a history of 8 weeks of amenorrhea. On examination, she is hemodynamically stable. Her beta hCG levels are measured at 2500 IU/L. After 48 hours, the beta hCG levels recorded are 1500 IU/L and the subsequent level recorded is 500 IU/L. TVS show no evidence of a gestational sac in the uterus and adnexa. What is the most likely diagnosis?
questions.explanation: Correct Answer: C) Non-viable Intrauterine Pregnancy Explanation: The most likely diagnosis is a non-viable intrauterine pregnancy (dying pregnancy). In a viable intrauterine pregnancy, beta hCG levels typically double every 48 hours. In this scenario, the beta hCG levels have fallen from 2500 IU/L to 2000 IU/L, and then to 1000 IU/L indicating a failing pregnancy. Diagnosis Based on Beta hCG Levels: Beta hCG Levels Condition Beta hCG levels double every 48 hours Viable Intrauterine Pregnancy (Option A) Beta hCG levels increase but not doubled (such as less than 35% in 48 hours) Unruptured Ectopic Pregnancy (Option B) Beta hCG levels decrease over time Non-viable Intrauterine Pregnancy Extremely high beta hCG level Molar Pregnancy (Option D) Choriocarcinoma Multiple Pregnancy Reference: Williams Obstetrics, 26th Edition, Page 222-226 www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5588477/

questions.question: A 27-year-old woman presents to the clinic with complaints of mild lower abdominal pain and vaginal spotting. She has a history of 6 weeks of amenorrhea. On examination, she is hemodynamically stable, and a transvaginal ultrasound (TVS) reveals an adnexal mass of 3cm consistent with an unruptured ectopic pregnancy. No fetal cardiac activity is found. Her initial beta hCG level is measured at 2,000 IU/L. What is the most appropriate management for this patient?
questions.explanation: Correct Answer: B) Methotrexate therapy Explanation: Methotrexate therapy is the most appropriate management for a hemodynamically stable patient with an unruptured ectopic pregnancy and a beta hCG level less than 3,000 IU/L, provided the adnexal mass is less than 4 cm and there is no fetal cardiac activity. Management of Unruptured Ectopic Tubal Pregnancy: Management Criteria/Indication Description Expectant Management Beta hCG < 1,500 IU/L No significant symptoms Strong likelihood of spontaneous resolution Monitoring without intervention, relying on the natural resolution of the ectopic pregnancy Medical Management Beta hCG < 3,000 IU/L Adnexal mass < 4 cm No fetal cardiac activity Hemodynamically stable Methotrexate (single dose/ multi-dose regimen) (best) KCl (directly in sac) Mifepristone Prostaglandins Surgical Management Beta hCG > 5,000 IU/L Size of ectopic > 4 cm Presence of cardiac activity Linear Salpingostomy (best) Resection Anastomosis Reference: Williams Obstetrics, 26th Edition, Page 222, 223

questions.question: Which of the following statements is true regarding methotrexate as treatment for unruptured ectopic pregnancy ?

options.A: Single dose of 100 mg/m² given intramuscularly
options.B: Decline in hCG of 15% or more between Day 1 and 3 indicates successful treatment
options.C: A single dose of 50 mg methotrexate is given intravenously.
options.D: A second dose of methotrexate given on Day 7 if decline in hCG is less than 15%

questions.explanation: 50 mg/m² given intramuscularly (Option A) (Option C) After administration, serum β -hCG levels are monitored on Day 4 and Day 7 A decline in hCG of 15% or more between Day 4 and Day 7 (Option B) indicates successful treatment, The patient is followed up weekly with serum hCG monitoring until the level falls below 10 mIU/mL. If the decline in hCG is less than 15% between Day 4 and Day 7, a second dose of methotrexate (50 mg/m²) may be given on Day 7. Reference: Williams Obstetrics, 26th Edition, Page 222, 223, 224, 225

questions.question: A 35-year-old woman’s transvaginal ultrasound reveals a 5 cm ectopic pregnancy located in the ampulla of the right fallopian tube. The initial serum beta hCG level was 3500 IU/L and has remained stable despite receiving three doses of methotrexate. What is the most appropriate management option for this patient?
questions.explanation: pregnancy in the right fallopian tube that has failed to respond to medical management with methotrexate. Laparoscopic salpingectomy involves the removal of the affected fallopian tube . It is indicated when medical therapy fails or is contraindicated, such as in cases of larger ectopic pregnancies (> 4 cm) or persistent beta hCG levels. Expectant management (Option A) involves observation of the patient, hoping for spontaneous resolution. This is a viable option in cases where the beta hCG level is low or falling. Hysterectomy (Option B) is not considered a management option for ectopic pregnancy. Laparoscopic linear salpingostomy (Option C) is a conservative surgical option, but it is less appropriate here after failed medical therapy and due to the size of the ectopic pregnancy. Reference: Williams Obstetrics, 26th Edition, Page 222, 223, 225, 226

questions.question: Which of the following is not an indication of expectant management of unruptured tubal pregnancy?

options.A: The initial beta hCG level is less than 2500 IU/L
options.C: Gestation sac size less than 4 cm
options.D: No evidence of bleeding on USG

questions.explanation: expectorant management of ectopic pregnancy: Initial serum hCG level is less than 1,500 IU/L and subsequent levels are decreasing. Gestational sac size is less than 4 cm . (Option C) Absence of fetal heartbeat detected (Option B) on transvaginal ultrasound (TVS). No evidence of bleeding (Option D) or rupture on transvaginal ultrasound (TVS). Reference: Williams Obstetrics, 26th Edition, Page222

questions.question: Which of the following statements about differentiating cornual and angular pregnancy is false? angular pregnancy. pregnancy.

options.A: The presence of an interstitial line sign on ultrasound is more specific for cornual pregnancy than for
options.B: Angular pregnancy is located medially to the round ligament.
options.C: Cornual pregnancy is typically associated with a thicker myometrial mantle than angular pregnancy.
options.D: Angular pregnancy carries a higher risk of uterine rupture compared to normal intrauterine

questions.explanation: than angular pregnancy. Correct Answer: C) Cornual pregnancy is typically associated with a thicker myometrial mantle than angular pregnancy. Explanation: Cornual pregnancy implants in the interstitial part of the fallopian tube or rudimentary horn, where the myometrial mantle is thin or absent. Angular pregnancy implants within the uterine cavity’s lateral angle, medial to the round ligament, and usually has a thicker myometrial mantle (>5 mm). Hence, cornual pregnancy does not have a thicker myometrium than angular pregnancy, making option C false. Angular Pregnancy vs Cornual Pregnancy: Feature Angular Pregnancy Cornual (Interstitial) Pregnancy Definition Implantation in the lateral angle of the uterine cavity, medial to the round ligament and near the uterotubal junction Implantation in the interstitial segment of the fallopian tube (within uterine wall but outside uterine cavity) or in a rudimentary horn of a malformed uterus Location Intrauterine but eccentric (lateral uterine angle) Extrauterine (interstitial segment) or rudimentary horn Relation to Round Ligament Medial to round ligament Lateral to round ligament (interstitial); variable in rudimentary horn Interstitial line sign Absent Present (specific finding on ultrasound) Myometrial Mantle Thickness Typically thick (>5 mm) Thin or absent, especially in rudimentary horn Prognosis Can progress to term but carries a high risk of rupture and hemorrhage High risk of early rupture and hemorrhage, especially in rudimentary horn Outcome May result in live birth but with significant risk Rarely progresses to term; high maternal morbidity risk Diagnosis Difficult; relies on imaging and relation to round ligament Difficult; imaging important to distinguish from angular pregnancy The presence of an interstitial line sign on ultrasound is more specific for cornual pregnancy than for angular pregnancy (Option A): Correct. The interstitial line sign is a hallmark of cornual pregnancy and helps distinguish it from angular pregnancy. Angular pregnancy is located medial to the round ligament (Option B): Correct and is a defining feature. Angular pregnancy carries a higher risk of uterine rupture compared to normal intrauterine pregnancy (Option D): Correct as it has increased risk of rupture and hemorrhage compared to normal pregnancy. Reference: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5558297/ https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10208802/ https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10553601/

questions.question: Which condition is Spiegelberg's criteria used to diagnose?
questions.explanation: pregnancy: The fallopian tube on the affected side must be intact. The gestational sac must be located within the ovary. The gestational sac is connected to the uterus via the ovarian ligament. Ovarian tissue must be identified on histological examination of the sac wall. Cesarean scar pregnancy(Option B) is defined as implantation into the myometrial defect in the site of the previous uterine scar Abdominal Pregnancy(Option C) Studdiford’s criteria is used for the diagnosis of Abdominal Pregnancy Cervical Pregnancy(Option D) Rubin’s criteria is used for the diagnosis of cervical pregnancy Reference: Williams Obstetrics, 26th Edition, Page231
